{0 'Kenya\'s coffee and tea growing areasremained generally dry for the second consecutive week, in theperiod to April 28, weather and farming sources said. All areas east and west of the Rift Valley recorded below25 mm of rain with western Kericho town having only 21 mm, theysaid. Kericho, which last year received 387 mm in April lastyear, has so far recorded only 176 mm and little rain isforecast throughout the country in the next two days. Tea and coffee crops are doing well but farmers fear thatoutput will be low if the unusually dry spell continues. Aprilis normally the wettest month in Kenya. Reuter',1 TEA}
